Gotcha :)
The commits of the PR has been squashed and pushed to master with JIRA issue number as commit message: https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/6120cedb5e24aa54b06fdb0ff880ba24018d3525

@paulk-asert @danielsun1106 Tests for \@CompileStatic added. I also noticed interesting behaviour:
```java
interface Foo {
  static void foo() {
    System.out.println("static void foo() called");
  }
}

class Bar implements Foo { }

Bar.foo() \\works in Groovy (dynamic) but doesn't compile in Java and Groovy (@CompileStatic) 
```
as per JLS8 - 8.4.8 Inheritance, Overriding, and Hiding

@paulk-asert Cool. About my previous comment. I've rechecked that case when a class doesn't hide static methods on the implemented interface and we try to call those methods on the class (not on the interface). In this situation Java just doesn't compile:
```java
interface Foo {
  static void foo() {
    System.out.println("static void foo() called");
  }
}

class Bar implements Foo { }

public class FooBarTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bar.foo();
    }
}
```
```bash
$ javac FooBarTest.java
FooBarTest.java:3: error: cannot find symbol
        Bar.foo();
           ^
  symbol:   method foo()
  location: class Bar
1 error
```
But Groovy does compile, both dynamic and \@CompileStatic. So I was wrong about \@CompileStatic point and here is a couple of questions:
1) Shouldn't \@CompileStatic behave like Java in this case?
2) Should we fix this?
3) Maybe both dynamic and \@CompileStatic Groovy should behave like Java?

I could investigate how it can be fixed if it should be

Just in case, here is a snippet from *JLS8*:
**8.4.8 Inheritance, Overriding, and Hiding**
A class C inherits from its direct superclass all concrete methods m (both **static** and instance) of the superclass for which all of the following are true:
...
A class does not inherit **static** methods from its superinterfaces.
